WEBVTT

00:21.580 --> 00:24.380
CHAPTER I.

00:24.980 --> 00:25.760
ECONOMY

00:26.440 --> 00:28.980
LibriVox Part III

00:29.900 --> 00:36.640
In the savage state every family owns a shelter as good as the best, and sufficient for its

00:36.640 --> 00:38.100
coarser and simpler wants.

00:39.420 --> 00:44.200
But I think that I speak within bounds when I say that, though the birds of the air have

00:44.200 --> 00:52.360
their nests, and the foxes their holes, and the savages their wigwams, in modern civilized

00:52.360 --> 00:57.600
society not more than one half the families own a shelter.

00:58.340 --> 01:05.500
In the large towns and cities where civilization especially prevails the number of those who

01:05.500 --> 01:09.420
own a shelter is a very small fraction of the whole.

01:10.460 --> 01:19.200
The rest pay an annual tax for this outside garment of all, become indispensable summer

01:19.200 --> 01:28.180
and winter, which would buy a village of Indian wigwams, but now helps to keep them poor as

01:28.180 --> 01:29.180
long as they live.

01:30.260 --> 01:38.140
I do not mean to insist here on the disadvantage of hiring compared with owning, but it is

01:38.140 --> 01:45.200
evident that the savage owns his shelter because it costs so little, while the civilized man

01:45.200 --> 01:52.900
hires his commonly because he cannot afford to own it, nor can he in the long run any

01:52.900 --> 01:54.680
better afford to hire.

01:56.060 --> 02:04.680
But answers one, by merely paying this tax the poor civilized man secures an abode which

02:04.680 --> 02:07.600
is a palace compared with the savages.

02:08.400 --> 02:16.220
An annual rent of from twenty-five to a hundred dollars, these are the country rates, entitles

02:16.220 --> 02:23.660
him to the benefit of the improvements of centuries, spacious apartments, clean paint

02:23.660 --> 02:31.940
and paper, Rumford fireplace, back plastering, Venetian blinds, copper pump, spring lock,

02:32.100 --> 02:34.300
a commodious cellar, and many other things.

02:34.680 --> 02:43.160
But how happens it that he who is said to enjoy these things is so commonly a poor civilized

02:43.160 --> 02:48.560
man while the savage who has them not is rich as a savage?

02:49.120 --> 02:55.540
If it is asserted that civilization is a real advance in the condition of man, and I think

02:55.540 --> 03:04.040
that it is, though only the wise improve their advantages, it must be shown that it has produced

03:04.040 --> 03:07.980
better dwellings without making them more costly.

03:09.120 --> 03:16.820
And the cost of a thing is the amount of what I will call life which is required to be exchanged

03:16.820 --> 03:20.940
for it, immediately or in the long run.

03:21.540 --> 03:28.340
An average house in this neighborhood costs perhaps eight hundred dollars, and to lay

03:28.340 --> 03:34.280
up this sum will take from ten to fifteen years of the laborer's life, even if he is

03:34.280 --> 03:40.940
not encumbered with a family, estimating the pecuniary value of every man's labor at one

03:40.940 --> 03:48.780
dollar a day, for if some receive more, others receive less, so that he must have spent more

03:48.780 --> 03:54.400
than half his life commonly before his wigwam will be earned.

03:54.860 --> 04:01.540
If we suppose him to pay a rent instead, this is but a doubtful choice of evils.

04:02.540 --> 04:08.240
Would the savage have been wise to exchange his wigwam for a palace on these terms?

04:08.920 --> 04:15.020
It may be guessed that I reduce almost the whole advantage of holding this superfluous

04:15.020 --> 04:22.060
property as a fund in store against the future, so far as the individual is concerned, mainly

04:22.060 --> 04:29.360
to the defraying of funeral expenses, but perhaps a man is not required to bury himself.

04:30.460 --> 04:36.500
Nevertheless, this points to an important distinction between civilized man and the

04:36.500 --> 04:43.220
savage, and no doubt they have designs on us for our benefit in making the life of a

04:43.220 --> 04:48.980
civilized people an institution in which the life of the individual is to a great extent

04:48.980 --> 04:54.060
absorbed in order to preserve and perfect that of the race.

04:54.700 --> 05:04.160
But I wish to show at what a sacrifice this advantage is at present obtained, and to suggest

05:04.160 --> 05:11.420
that we may possibly so live as to secure all the advantage without suffering any of

05:11.420 --> 05:12.380
the disadvantage.

05:13.080 --> 05:19.480
What mean ye by saying that the poor ye have always with you, or that the fathers have

05:19.480 --> 05:23.180
eaten sour grapes and the children's teeth are set on edge?

05:23.780 --> 05:31.220
As I live, saith the Lord God, ye shall not have occasion any more to use this proverb

05:31.700 --> 05:32.900
in Israel.

05:33.660 --> 05:36.720
Behold, all souls are mine.

05:37.080 --> 05:42.320
As the soul of the father soul, also the soul of the son is mine.

05:42.920 --> 05:46.560
The soul that sinneth, it shall die.

05:47.000 --> 05:53.360
When I consider my neighbors, the farmers of Concord, who are at least as well off as

05:53.360 --> 06:00.640
the other classes, I find that for the most part they have been toiling twenty, thirty,

06:00.640 --> 06:08.340
or forty years that they may become the real owners of their farms, which commonly they

06:08.340 --> 06:15.960
have inherited with encumbrances, or else bought with hired money, and we may regard

06:15.960 --> 06:22.300
one third of that toil as the cost of their houses, but commonly they have not paid for

06:22.300 --> 06:23.060
them yet.

06:23.440 --> 06:24.460
It is true.

06:24.460 --> 06:30.880
The encumbrances sometimes outweigh the value of the farm, so that the farm itself becomes

06:30.880 --> 06:39.120
one great encumbrance, and still a man is found to inherit it, being well acquainted

06:39.120 --> 06:40.640
with it, as he says.

06:41.780 --> 06:47.860
On applying to the assessors, I am surprised to learn that they cannot at once name a dozen

06:47.860 --> 06:52.020
in the town who own their farms free and clear.

06:53.000 --> 06:58.560
If you would know the history of these homesteads, inquire at the bank where they are mortgaged.

06:59.340 --> 07:07.060
The man who has actually paid for his farm with labor on it is so rare that every neighbor

07:07.060 --> 07:08.240
can point to him.

07:09.380 --> 07:12.600
I doubt if there are three such men in Concord.

07:13.580 --> 07:18.360
What has been said of the merchants, that a very large majority, even ninety-seven

07:18.360 --> 07:22.460
in a hundred are sure to fail, is equally true of the farmers.

07:23.780 --> 07:29.320
With regard to the merchants, however, one of them says pertinently that a great part

07:29.320 --> 07:36.520
of their failures are not genuine pecuniary failures, but merely failures to fulfill their

07:36.520 --> 07:39.660
engagements, because it is inconvenient.

07:40.500 --> 07:43.860
That is, it is the moral character that breaks down.

07:44.530 --> 07:50.740
But this puts an infinitely worse face on the matter, and suggests, besides, that probably

07:50.740 --> 07:58.000
not even the other three succeed in saving their souls, but are perchance bankrupt in

07:58.000 --> 08:01.060
a worse sense than they who fail honestly.

08:02.790 --> 08:08.560
Bankruptcy and repudiation are the springboards from which much of our civilization vaults

08:09.000 --> 08:17.420
its summer sets, but the savage stands on the unelastic plank of famine.

08:18.560 --> 08:24.580
Yet the middle-sex cattle show goes off here with Iclas annually, as if all the joints

08:24.580 --> 08:27.200
of the agricultural machine were suant.

08:28.580 --> 08:35.520
The farmer is endeavoring to solve the problem of a livelihood by a formula more complicated

08:35.520 --> 08:36.940
than the problem itself.

08:37.700 --> 08:42.240
To get his shoestrings he speculates in herds of cattle.

08:43.100 --> 08:50.820
With consummate skill he has set his trap with a hair-spring to catch comfort and independence,

08:51.060 --> 08:55.160
and then, as he turned away, got his own leg into it.

08:56.040 --> 09:03.120
This is the reason he is poor, and for a similar reason we are all poor in respect to a thousand

09:03.120 --> 09:06.980
savage comforts, though surrounded by luxuries.

09:07.900 --> 09:09.520
As Chapman sings,

09:20.880 --> 09:28.880
And when the farmer has got his house, he may not be the richer but the poorer for it,

09:28.880 --> 09:31.380
and it be the house that has got him.

09:32.220 --> 09:40.160
As I understand it, that was a valid objection urged by Mommus against the house which Minerva

09:40.160 --> 09:48.160
made, that she had not made it movable, by which means a bad neighborhood might be avoided.

09:50.340 --> 09:56.940
And it may still be urged, for our houses are such unwieldy property that we are often

09:56.940 --> 10:03.240
imprisoned rather than housed in them, and the bad neighborhood to be avoided is our

10:03.240 --> 10:05.300
own scurvy selves.

10:06.920 --> 10:13.000
I know one or two families, at least, in this town, who for nearly a generation have been

10:13.000 --> 10:19.340
wishing to sell their houses in the outskirts and move into the village, but have not been

10:19.340 --> 10:24.020
able to accomplish it, and only death will set them free.

10:24.760 --> 10:30.880
Granted that the majority are able, at last, either to own or hire the modern house with

10:30.880 --> 10:32.080
all its improvements.

10:33.660 --> 10:39.360
While civilization has been improving our houses, it has not equally improved the men

10:39.360 --> 10:41.180
who are to inhabit them.

10:42.380 --> 10:49.260
It has created palaces, but it was not so easy to create noblemen and kings.

10:50.060 --> 10:56.660
And if the civilized man's pursuits are no worthier than the savage's, if he is employed

10:56.660 --> 11:03.000
the greater part of his life in obtaining gross necessaries and comforts merely, why

11:03.000 --> 11:06.200
should he have a better dwelling than the former?

11:07.480 --> 11:10.540
But how do the poor minority fare?

11:11.440 --> 11:17.980
Perhaps it will be found that just in proportion, as some have been placed in outward circumstances

11:17.980 --> 11:22.580
above the savage, others have been degraded below him.

11:23.820 --> 11:29.640
The luxury of one class is counterbalanced by the indigence of another.

11:30.920 --> 11:39.380
On the one side is the palace, on the other are the almshouse and silent poor.

11:40.360 --> 11:47.440
The myriads who built the pyramids to be the tombs of the pharaohs were fed on garlic,

11:48.060 --> 11:51.860
and it may be were not decently varied themselves.

11:52.920 --> 11:58.900
The mason who finishes the cornice of the palace returns at night perchance to a hut

11:58.900 --> 12:01.100
not so good as a wigwam.

12:01.760 --> 12:09.600
It is a mistake to suppose that in a country where the usual evidences of civilization

12:09.600 --> 12:17.980
exist the condition of a very large body of the inhabitants may not be as degraded as

12:17.980 --> 12:19.240
that of savages.

12:20.580 --> 12:26.200
I refer to the degraded poor, not now to the degraded rich.

12:27.200 --> 12:33.960
To know this, I should not need to look farther than to the shanties which everywhere border

12:33.960 --> 12:42.920
our railroads, that last improvement in civilization, where I see in my daily walks human beings

12:42.920 --> 12:51.460
living in sties, and all winter with an open door, for the sake of light, without any visible,

12:51.460 --> 12:58.500
often imaginable, wood-pile, and the forms of both old and young are permanently contracted

12:58.500 --> 13:05.300
by the long habit of shrinking from cold and misery, and the development of all their limbs

13:05.300 --> 13:07.020
and faculties is checked.

13:08.160 --> 13:13.780
It certainly is fair to look at that class by whose labor the works which distinguish

13:13.780 --> 13:15.920
this generation are accomplished.

13:17.040 --> 13:25.080
Such, too, to a greater or less extent, is the condition of the operatives of every denomination

13:25.080 --> 13:29.040
in England, which is the great workhouse of the world.

13:30.160 --> 13:36.940
Or, I could refer you to Ireland, which is marked as one of the white or enlightened

13:36.940 --> 13:38.240
spots on the map.

13:39.540 --> 13:45.320
Contrast the physical condition of the Irish with that of the North American Indian, or

13:45.320 --> 13:51.240
the South Sea Islander, or any other savage race before it was degraded by contact with

13:51.240 --> 13:52.520
the civilized man.

13:54.140 --> 14:01.820
Yet I have no doubt that that people's rulers are as wise as the average of civilized rulers.

14:03.480 --> 14:09.800
Their condition only proves what squalidness may consist with civilization.

14:10.700 --> 14:18.780
I hardly need refer now to the laborers in our southern states, who produce the staple

14:18.780 --> 14:27.300
exports of this country, and are themselves a staple production of the South, but to confine

14:27.300 --> 14:32.440
myself to those who are said to be in moderate circumstances.

14:33.520 --> 14:41.600
Most men appear never to have considered what a house is, and are actually, though needlessly,

14:42.220 --> 14:49.060
poor all their lives because they think that they must have such a one as their neighbors

14:49.060 --> 14:49.720
have.

14:50.600 --> 14:59.680
As if one were to wear any sort of coat which the tailor might cut out for him, or, gradually

14:59.680 --> 15:06.780
leaving off palm-leaf hat or cap of woodchuck skin, complain of hard times because he could

15:06.780 --> 15:08.760
not afford to buy him a crown.

15:10.060 --> 15:17.960
It is possible to invent a house still more convenient and luxurious than we have, which

15:17.960 --> 15:22.280
yet all would admit that man could not afford to pay for.

15:22.280 --> 15:30.200
Shall we always study to obtain more of these things, and not sometimes to be content with

15:30.200 --> 15:30.720
less?

15:32.340 --> 15:39.960
Shall the respectable citizen thus gravely teach by precept and example the necessity

15:39.960 --> 15:47.980
of the young man's providing a certain number of superfluous glow-shoes and umbrellas and

15:47.980 --> 15:52.980
empty guest chambers for empty guests before he dies?

15:54.160 --> 16:01.800
Why should not our furniture be as simple as the Arabs' or the Indians'?

16:02.300 --> 16:09.540
When I think of the benefactors of the race, whom we have apotheosized as messengers from

16:09.540 --> 16:17.960
heaven, bearers of divine gifts to man, I do not see in my mind that there is no such

16:17.980 --> 16:24.740
any retinue at their heels, any carload of fashionable furniture.

16:25.840 --> 16:34.580
Or what if I were to allow, would it not be a singular allowance, that our furniture should

16:34.580 --> 16:44.140
be more complex than the Arabs' in proportion as we are morally and intellectually his superiors?

16:45.260 --> 16:52.900
At present our houses are cluttered and defiled with it, and a good housewife would sweep

16:52.900 --> 16:58.260
out the greater part into the dust-hole and not leave her morning's work undone.

16:59.900 --> 17:14.120
Morning work! By the blushes of aurora and the music of memnon, what should be man's

17:14.120 --> 17:14.360
property?

17:14.860 --> 17:22.040
Pieces of limestone on my desk, but I was terrified to find that they required to be

17:22.040 --> 17:31.160
dusted daily, when the furniture of my mind was all undusted still, and threw them out

17:31.160 --> 17:39.680
the window in disgust. How then could I have a furnished house? I would rather sit in the

17:39.680 --> 17:48.860
open air, for no dust gathers on the grass, unless where man has broken ground. It is

17:48.860 --> 17:57.340
the luxurious and dissipated who set the fashions which the herd so diligently follow. The traveler

17:57.340 --> 18:04.760
who stops at the best houses so called soon discovers this, for the publicans presume

18:04.760 --> 18:14.200
him to be a sardinopolis, and if he resigned himself to their tender mercies he would soon

18:14.200 --> 18:23.320
be completely emasculated. I think that in the railroad car we are inclined to spend

18:23.320 --> 18:30.660
more on luxury than on safety and convenience, and it threatens without attaining these to

18:30.660 --> 18:38.260
become no better than a modern drawing-room, with its divans and ottomans and sunshades

18:38.260 --> 18:44.720
and a hundred other oriental things, which we are taking west with us, invented for the

18:44.720 --> 18:52.260
ladies of the harem and the effeminate natives of the celestial empire which Jonathan should

18:52.260 --> 19:00.080
be ashamed to know the names of. I would rather sit on a pumpkin and have it all to myself

19:00.080 --> 19:09.980
than be crowded on a velvet cushion. I would rather ride on earth in an ox cart with a

19:09.980 --> 19:16.480
free circulation than go to heaven in the fancy car of an excursion train and breathe

19:16.480 --> 19:24.200
a malaria all the way. The very simplicity and nakedness of man's life in the primitive

19:24.200 --> 19:33.420
ages imply this advantage, at least, that they left him still but a sojourner in nature.

19:34.400 --> 19:41.880
When he was refreshed with food and sleep he contemplated his journey again. He dwelt,

19:41.980 --> 19:49.420
as it were, in a tent in this world, and was either threading the valleys or crossing the

19:49.420 --> 19:57.540
plains or climbing the mountain tops. But lo, men have become the tools of their tools.

19:58.820 --> 20:05.560
The man who independently plucked the fruits when he was hungry has become a farmer, and

20:05.560 --> 20:14.140
he who stood under a tree for shelter a housekeeper. We now no longer camp as for a night, but

20:14.140 --> 20:21.080
have settled down on earth and forgotten heaven. We have adopted Christianity merely

20:21.080 --> 20:29.920
as an improved method of agriculture. We have built for this world a family mansion and

20:29.920 --> 20:38.200
for the next a family tomb. The best works of art are the expression of man's struggle

20:38.200 --> 20:45.980
to free himself from this condition, but the effect of our art is merely to make this low

20:45.980 --> 20:55.620
state comfortable and that higher state to be forgotten. There is actually no place in

20:55.620 --> 21:05.080
this village for a work of fine art, if any had come down to us, to stand. For our lives

21:05.570 --> 21:14.080
our houses and streets furnish no proper pedestal for it. There is not a nail to hang a picture

21:14.080 --> 21:24.540
on or a shelf to receive the bust of a hero or a saint. When I consider how our houses

21:24.540 --> 21:34.080
are built and paid for or not paid for, and their internal economy managed and sustained,

21:35.080 --> 21:39.580
I wonder that the floor does not give way under the visitor while he is admiring the

21:39.580 --> 21:48.660
gougas upon the mantelpiece, and let him through into the cellar to some solid and honest though

21:48.660 --> 21:59.620
earthy foundation. I cannot but perceive that this so-called rich and refined life is a

21:59.620 --> 22:06.920
thing jumped at, and I do not get on in the enjoyment of the fine arts which adorn it,

22:07.740 --> 22:17.080
my attention being wholly occupied with the jump. For I remember that the greatest genuine

22:17.080 --> 22:29.600
leap due to human muscles alone, on record, is that of certain wandering Arabs who are

22:29.880 --> 22:37.340
on level ground. Without factitious support, man is sure to come to earth again beyond

22:37.340 --> 22:43.560
that distance. The first question which I am tempted to put to the proprietor of such

22:43.560 --> 22:53.780
great impropriety is, Who bolsters you? Are you one of the ninety-seven who fail, or the

22:53.780 --> 23:01.020
three who succeed? Answer me these questions, and then perhaps I may look at your baubles

23:01.020 --> 23:08.720
and find them ornamental. The cart before the horse is neither beautiful nor useful.

23:09.760 --> 23:16.360
Before we can adorn our houses with beautiful objects, the walls must be stripped, and our

23:16.360 --> 23:22.800
lives must be stripped, and beautiful housekeeping and beautiful living be laid for a foundation.

23:24.460 --> 23:35.320
Now a taste for the beautiful is most cultivated out of doors, where there is no house and

23:35.320 --> 23:45.300
no housekeeper. Old Johnson, in his wonder-working Providence, speaking of the first settlers

23:45.300 --> 23:53.760
of this town, with whom he was contemporary, tells us that, They burrow themselves in the

23:53.780 --> 24:01.720
earth for their first shelter under some hillside, and, casting the soil aloft upon timber, they

24:01.720 --> 24:11.120
make a smoky fire against the earth at the highest side. They did not provide them houses,

24:11.860 --> 24:23.040
says he, till the earth, by the Lord's blessing, brought forth bread to feed them. And the

24:23.040 --> 24:30.380
first year's crop was so light that, They were forced to cut their bread very thin for

24:30.840 --> 24:40.640
a long season. The Secretary of the Province of New Netherland, writing in Dutch in 1650,

24:41.040 --> 24:45.480
for the information of those who wished to take up land there, states more particularly

24:45.480 --> 24:53.020
that, Those in New Netherland, and especially in New England, who have no means to build

24:53.020 --> 24:59.540
farmhouses, at first, according to their wishes, dig a square pit in the ground, cellar fashion,

25:00.120 --> 25:06.620
six or seven feet deep, as long and as broad as they think proper, case the earth inside

25:06.620 --> 25:13.520
with wood all around the wall, and line the wood with the bark of trees or something else

25:13.520 --> 25:19.820
to prevent the caving in of the earth, floor this cellar with plank, and wainscotted overhead

25:19.820 --> 25:27.070
for a ceiling, raise a roof of spars, clear up, and cover the spars with bark or green

25:28.080 --> 25:33.940
sods, so that they can live dry and warm in these houses with their entire families for

25:33.940 --> 25:42.200
two, three, and four years, it being understood that partitions are run through these cellars

25:42.200 --> 25:48.340
which are adapted to the size of the family. The wealthy and principal men in New England,

25:48.760 --> 25:53.600
in the beginning of the colonies, commenced their first dwelling houses in this fashion

25:53.600 --> 26:01.720
for two reasons. Firstly, in order not to waste time in building, and not to want food

26:01.720 --> 26:09.300
the next season. Secondly, in order not to discourage poor laboring people, whom they

26:09.300 --> 26:14.340
brought over in numbers from fatherland, in the course of three or four years when the

26:14.340 --> 26:21.480
country became adapted to agriculture, they built themselves handsome houses, spending

26:21.480 --> 26:29.620
on them several thousands. In this course which our ancestors took there was a show

26:29.620 --> 26:36.720
of prudence, at least, as if their principle were to satisfy the more pressing wants first.

26:38.860 --> 26:46.260
But are the more pressing wants satisfied now? When I think of acquiring for myself

26:46.260 --> 26:55.880
one of our luxurious dwellings, I am deterred, for, so to speak, the country is not yet adapted

26:55.880 --> 27:03.660
to human culture, and we are still forced to cut our spiritual bread far thinner than

27:03.660 --> 27:11.220
our forefathers did their Wheaton. Not that all architectural ornament is to be neglected,

27:11.700 --> 27:21.060
even in the rudest periods, but let our houses first be lined with beauty, where they come

27:21.060 --> 27:29.980
in contact with our lives, like the tenement of the shellfish, and not overlaid with it.

27:32.100 --> 27:40.720
But, alas! I have been inside one or two of them, and know what they are lined with.

27:41.800 --> 27:47.240
Though we are not so degenerate, but that we might possibly live in a cave or a wigwam

27:47.240 --> 27:58.700
or wear skins to-day, it certainly is better to accept the advantages, though so dearly

27:58.700 --> 28:06.180
offered. In such a neighborhood as this, boards and shingles, lime and bricks are cheaper

28:06.180 --> 28:13.160
and more easily obtained than suitable caves, or whole logs, or bark in sufficient quantities,

28:13.300 --> 28:21.800
or even well-tempered clay, or flat stones. I speak understandingly on this subject, for

28:21.800 --> 28:25.780
I have made myself acquainted with it both theoretically and practically.

28:26.900 --> 28:33.400
With a little more wit we might use these materials so as to become richer than the

28:33.400 --> 28:42.220
richest now are, and make our civilization a blessing. The civilized man is a more experienced

28:42.800 --> 28:51.620
and wiser savage, but to make haste to my own experiment. Near the end of March, 1845,

28:52.080 --> 28:59.700
I borrowed an axe and went down to the woods by Walden Pond, nearest to where I intended

28:59.700 --> 29:06.560
to build my house, and began to cut down some tall, arrowy white pines, still in their youth

29:06.560 --> 29:15.040
for timber. It is difficult to begin without borrowing, but perhaps it is the most generous

29:15.040 --> 29:21.700
course, thus to permit your fellow man to have an interest in your enterprise. The owner

29:21.700 --> 29:29.140
of the axe, as he released his hold on it, said that it was the apple of his eye, but

29:29.140 --> 29:34.940
I returned it sharper than I received it. It was a pleasant hillside where I worked,

29:35.460 --> 29:42.800
covered with pine woods, through which I looked out on the pond, and a small open field in

29:42.800 --> 29:48.340
the woods, where pines and hickories were springing up. The ice in the pond was not

29:48.340 --> 29:55.200
yet dissolved, though there were some open spaces, and it was all dark-colored and saturated

29:55.200 --> 30:01.240
with water. There were some slight flurries of snow during the days that I worked there,

30:01.980 --> 30:07.780
but for the most part when I came out, on to the railroad on my way home, its yellow

30:07.780 --> 30:14.600
sand-heap stretched away gleaming in the hazy atmosphere, and the rails shone in the spring

30:14.600 --> 30:21.880
sun, and I heard the lark and powee and other birds already come to commence another year

30:21.880 --> 30:30.820
with us. They were pleasant spring days, in which the winter of man's discontent was thawing

30:30.820 --> 30:37.720
as well as the earth, and the life that had lain torpid began to stretch itself.

30:39.720 --> 30:47.460
One day, when my axe had come off and I had cut a green hickory for a wedge, driving it

30:47.460 --> 30:53.600
with a stone, and had placed the hole to soak in a pond-hole in order to swell the wood,

30:54.480 --> 31:02.920
I saw a striped snake run into the water and he lay on the bottom, apparently without inconvenience,

31:03.560 --> 31:10.040
as long as I stayed there, or more than a quarter of an hour, perhaps because he had

31:10.040 --> 31:17.080
not yet fairly come out of the torpid state. It appeared to me that for a likely reason

31:17.520 --> 31:27.260
men remain in their present low and primitive condition. But if they should feel the influence

31:27.260 --> 31:36.040
of the spring of springs arousing them, they would of necessity rise to a higher and more

31:36.040 --> 31:43.740
ethereal life. I had previously seen the snakes in frosty mornings in my path, with portions

31:43.740 --> 31:51.740
of their body still numb and inflexible, waiting for the sun to thaw them. On the 1st of April

31:51.740 --> 31:58.640
it rained and melted the ice, and in the early part of the day, which was very foggy,

31:59.120 --> 32:06.880
I heard a stray goose groping about over the pond and cackling as if lost, or like the

32:06.880 --> 32:12.320
spirit of the fog. So I went on for some days cutting and hewing

32:12.320 --> 32:21.640
timber, and also studs and rafters, all with my narrow axe, not having many communicable

32:21.640 --> 32:30.900
or scholar-like thoughts, singing to myself, Men say they know many things, but lo, they

32:30.900 --> 32:39.560
have taken wings! The arts and sciences and a thousand appliances, the wind that blows

32:39.560 --> 32:48.860
is all that anybody knows. I hewed the main timbers six inches square, most of the studs

32:48.860 --> 32:55.800
on two sides only, and the rafters and floor timbers on one side, leaving the rest of the

32:55.800 --> 33:09.540
bark on, so that they were just as straight and much stronger than the sawed ones. Each

33:09.540 --> 33:16.520
had borrowed other tools by this time. My days in the woods were not very long ones,

33:17.360 --> 33:22.800
yet I usually carried my dinner of bread and butter, and read the newspaper in which it

33:22.800 --> 33:30.740
was wrapped, at noon, sitting amid the green pine boughs which I had cut off, and to my

33:30.740 --> 33:36.180
bread was imparted some of their fragrance, for my hands were covered with a thick coat

33:36.180 --> 33:45.160
of pitch. Before I had done I was more the friend than the foe of the pine tree, though

33:45.160 --> 33:52.180
I had cut down some of them, having become better acquainted with it. Sometimes a rambler

33:52.180 --> 33:58.020
in the wood was attracted by the sound of my axe, and we chatted pleasantly over the

33:58.020 --> 34:05.300
chips which I had made. By the middle of April, for I made no haste in my work, but rather

34:05.300 --> 34:13.720
made the most of it. My house was framed and ready for the raising. I had already bought

34:13.720 --> 34:19.820
the shanty of James Collins, an Irishman who worked on the Fitchburg Railroad for boards.

34:20.640 --> 34:27.460
James Collins' shanty was considered an uncommonly fine one. When I called to see it he was not

34:27.460 --> 34:34.700
at home. I walked about the outside at first unobserved from within, the windows were so

34:34.700 --> 34:42.880
deep and high. It was of small dimensions, with a peaked cottage roof, and not much

34:42.880 --> 34:50.060
else to be seen, the dirt being raised five feet all around as if it were a compost heap.

34:50.880 --> 34:59.200
The roof was the soundest part, though a good deal warped and made brittle by the sun. Door

34:59.200 --> 35:07.680
still there was none but a perennial passage for the hens under the door-board. Mrs. C.

35:07.900 --> 35:13.960
came to the door and asked me to view it from the inside. The hens were driven in by my

35:13.960 --> 35:22.800
approach. It was dark, and had a dirt floor for the most part, dank, clammy, and egwish,

35:23.480 --> 35:30.160
only here a board and there a board, which would not bear removal. She lighted a lamp

35:30.160 --> 35:36.180
to show me the inside of the roof and the walls, and also that the board floor extended

35:36.180 --> 35:42.640
under the bed, warning me not to step into the cellar, a sort of dust hole two feet deep.

35:43.240 --> 35:49.620
In her own words they were good boards overhead, good boards all around, and a good window

35:50.560 --> 35:57.460
of two whole squares originally, only the cat had passed out that way lately. There

35:57.460 --> 36:05.800
was a stove, a bed, and a place to sit, an infant in the house where it was born, a silk

36:05.800 --> 36:14.100
parasol, gilt-framed looking-glass, and a patent new coffee-mill nailed to an oak sapling,

36:14.100 --> 36:15.100
all told.

36:16.120 --> 36:22.360
The bargain was soon concluded, for James had in the meantime returned. I, to pay four

36:22.360 --> 36:29.060
dollars and twenty-five cents tonight, he to vacate at five tomorrow morning, selling

36:29.060 --> 36:37.100
to nobody else meanwhile, I to take possession at six. It were well, he said, to be there

36:37.100 --> 36:43.100
early and anticipate certain indistinct but wholly unjust claims on the score of ground

36:43.100 --> 36:48.260
rent and fuel. This, he assured me, was the only encumbrance.

36:49.380 --> 36:57.000
At six I passed him and his family on the road. One large bundle held their all, bed,

36:57.780 --> 37:06.140
coffee-mill, looking-glass, hens, all but the cat. She took to the woods and became

37:06.140 --> 37:14.440
a wild cat, and, as I learned afterward, trod in a trap set for wood-chucks, and so

37:14.440 --> 37:20.660
became a dead cat at last. I took down this dwelling the same morning, drawing the nails

37:20.660 --> 37:27.700
and removed it to the pond-side by small cartloads, spreading the boards on the grass there to

37:27.700 --> 37:34.760
bleach and warp back again in the sun. One early thrush gave me a note or two as I drove

37:34.760 --> 37:42.860
along the woodland path. I was informed treacherously by a young Patrick that neighbour Seeley,

37:43.140 --> 37:49.480
an Irishman, in the intervals of the carting, transferred the still tolerable, straight

37:49.480 --> 37:56.820
and drivable nails, staples, and spikes to his pocket, and then stood when I came back

37:56.820 --> 38:03.540
to pass the time of day and look freshly up, unconcerned with spring thoughts, at the devastation.

38:04.060 --> 38:10.820
There being a dearth of work, as he said, he was there to represent spectatordom and

38:10.820 --> 38:16.900
help make this seemingly insignificant event one with the removal of the gods of Troy.

38:17.620 --> 38:24.240
I dug my cellar in the side of a hill sloping to the south, where a wood-chuck had formerly

38:24.240 --> 38:32.160
dug his burrow, down through sumac and blackberry roots, and the lowest stain of vegetation,

38:32.500 --> 38:40.380
six feet square by seven deep, to a fine sand where potatoes would not freeze in any winter.

38:41.480 --> 38:48.900
The sides were left shelving and not stoned, but the sun having never shone on them the

38:48.900 --> 38:56.480
sand still keeps its place. It was but two hours' work. I took particular pleasure in

38:56.480 --> 39:04.660
this breaking of ground, for in almost all latitudes men dig into the earth for an equable

39:04.660 --> 39:12.380
temperature. Under the most splendid house in the city is still to be found the cellar,

39:12.620 --> 39:18.560
where they store their roots as of old, and long after the superstructure has disappeared

39:18.560 --> 39:26.460
posterity remark its dent in the earth. The house is still but a sort of portico, and

39:26.480 --> 39:34.400
a porch at the entrance of a burrow. At length in the beginning of May, with the help of

39:34.400 --> 39:39.980
some of my acquaintances, rather to improve so good an occasion for neighborliness than

39:39.980 --> 39:47.240
from any necessity, I set up the frame of my house. No man was ever more honored in

39:47.240 --> 39:53.460
the character of his razors than I. They are destined, I trust, to assist at the raising

39:53.460 --> 40:01.160
of loftier structures one day. I began to occupy my house on the fourth of July, as

40:01.160 --> 40:06.980
soon as it was boarded and roofed, for the boards were carefully feather-edged and lapped,

40:07.060 --> 40:14.120
so that it was perfectly impervious to rain. But before boarding I laid the foundation

40:14.120 --> 40:20.440
of a chimney at one end, bringing two cartloads of stones up the hill from the pond in my

40:20.440 --> 40:28.920
arms. I built the chimney after my hoeing in the fall, before a fire became necessary

40:28.920 --> 40:35.460
for warmth, doing my cooking in the meanwhile out of doors on the ground, early in the morning,

40:36.300 --> 40:41.560
which mode I still think is in some respects more convenient and agreeable than the usual

40:41.560 --> 40:49.380
one. When it stormed before my bread was baked I fixed a few boards over the fire and sat

40:49.380 --> 40:57.780
under them to watch my loaf, and passed some pleasant hours in that way. In those days

40:57.780 --> 41:06.120
when my hands were much employed I read but little, but the least scraps of paper which

41:06.120 --> 41:13.660
lay on the ground, my holder or tablecloth, afforded me as much entertainment, in fact

41:14.140 --> 41:21.280
answered the same purpose as the Iliad. It would be worth the while to build still more

41:21.280 --> 41:28.780
deliberately than I did, considering, for instance, what foundation a door, a window,

41:29.140 --> 41:38.080
a cellar, a garret, have in the nature of man, and, perchance, never raising any superstructure

41:38.080 --> 41:46.080
until we found a better reason for it than our temporal necessities even. There is some

41:46.080 --> 41:52.860
of the same fitness in a man's building his own house that there is in a bird's building

41:52.860 --> 42:01.220
its own nest. Who knows but if men constructed their dwellings with their own hands and provided

42:01.220 --> 42:09.700
food for themselves and families simply and honestly enough the poetic faculty would be

42:09.700 --> 42:18.300
universally developed as birds universally sing when they are so engaged. But, alas,

42:18.920 --> 42:25.500
we do like cow-birds and cuckoos which lay their eggs in nests which other birds have

42:25.500 --> 42:34.260
built, and cheer no traveller with their chattering and unmusical notes. Shall we forever resign

42:34.260 --> 42:41.520
the pleasure of construction to the carpenter? What does architecture amount to in the experience

42:41.520 --> 42:51.160
of the mass of men? I never in all my walks came across a man engaged in so simple and

42:51.160 --> 43:00.760
natural an occupation as building his house. We belong to the community. It is not the

43:00.760 --> 43:07.960
tailor alone who is the ninth part of a man. It is as much the preacher and the merchant

43:07.960 --> 43:18.500
and the farmer. Where is this division of labour to end? And what object does it finally

43:18.500 --> 43:27.060
serve? No doubt another may also think for me, but it is not therefore desirable that

43:27.060 --> 43:35.840
he should do so to the exclusion of my thinking for myself. True, there are architects so

43:35.840 --> 43:41.220
called in this country, and I have heard of one at least possessed with the idea of making

43:41.220 --> 43:48.480
architectural ornaments have a core of truth, a necessity, and hence a beauty. But I do

43:48.500 --> 43:55.100
not know of a beauty as if it were a revelation to him. All very well, perhaps from his point

43:55.100 --> 44:03.140
of view, but only a little better than the common dilettantism. A sentimental reformer

44:03.140 --> 44:11.880
in architecture he began at the cornice, not at the foundation. It was only how to put

44:11.880 --> 44:19.300
a core of truth within the ornaments that every sugar plum, in fact, might have an almond

44:19.300 --> 44:25.120
or caraway seed in it, though I hold that almonds are most wholesome without the sugar,

44:26.080 --> 44:33.660
and not how the inhabitant, the indweller, might build truly within and without and let

44:33.660 --> 44:41.860
the ornaments take care of themselves. What reasonable man ever supposed that ornaments

44:42.300 --> 44:51.440
were something outward and in the skin merely, that the tortoise got his spotted shell, or

44:51.440 --> 44:59.040
the shellfish its mother-of-pearl tints by such a contract as the inhabitants of Broadway

44:59.040 --> 45:07.500
their Trinity Church. But a man has no more to do with the style of architecture of his

45:07.500 --> 45:16.060
house than a tortoise with that of its shell. Nor need the soldier be so idle as to try

45:16.060 --> 45:23.520
to paint the precise colour of his virtue on his standard. The enemy will find it out.

45:24.660 --> 45:33.280
He may turn pale when the trial comes. This man seemed to me to lean over the cornice

45:33.280 --> 45:39.320
and timidly whisper his half-truth to the rude occupants, who really knew it better

45:39.320 --> 45:48.300
than he. What of architectural beauty I now see, I know has gradually grown from within

45:48.300 --> 45:56.380
outward, out of the necessities and character of the indweller, who is the only builder,

45:56.380 --> 46:05.960
out of some unconscious truthfulness and nobleness without ever a thought for the appearance

46:05.960 --> 46:12.140
and what additional beauty of this kind is destined to be produced will be preceded by

46:12.140 --> 46:23.080
a like unconscious beauty of life. The most interesting dwellings in this country, as

46:23.080 --> 46:33.360
pretending, humble log huts and cottages of the poor commonly, it is the life of the

46:33.360 --> 46:40.600
inhabitants whose shells they are, and not any peculiarity in their surfaces merely which

46:40.600 --> 46:50.400
make them picturesque. And equally interesting will be the citizen's suburban box when his

46:50.400 --> 46:59.060
life shall be as simple and as agreeable to the imagination, and there is as little straining

46:59.060 --> 47:06.720
after effect in the style of his dwelling. A great proportion of architectural ornaments

47:06.720 --> 47:14.800
are literally hollow, and a September gale would strip them off like borrowed plumes

47:15.020 --> 47:22.820
without injury to the substantials. They can do without architecture, who have no olives

47:22.820 --> 47:31.560
nor wines in the cellar. What if an equal ado were made about the ornaments of style

47:31.560 --> 47:39.780
in literature, and the architects of our Bibles spent as much time about their cornices as

47:39.780 --> 47:48.720
the architects of our churches do? So are made the belletres and the beaux-arts and

47:48.720 --> 47:55.920
their professors. Much it concerns a man forsooth how a few sticks are slanted over him or under

47:55.920 --> 48:05.280
him, and what colors are daubed upon his box. It would signify somewhat if, in any earnest

48:05.280 --> 48:13.000
sense, he slanted them and daubed it. But the spirit, having departed out of the tenant,

48:13.900 --> 48:23.060
it is of a piece with constructing his own coffin, the architecture of the grave. And

48:23.060 --> 48:31.840
carpenter is but another name for coffin-maker. One man says, in his despair or indifference

48:31.840 --> 48:40.180
to life, take up a handful of the earth at your feet and paint your house that color.

48:41.220 --> 48:51.100
Is he thinking of his last and narrow house? Toss up a copper for it as well. What an abundance

48:51.100 --> 48:59.560
of leisure he must have! Why do you take up a handful of dirt? Better paint your house

48:59.560 --> 49:10.580
your own complexion. Let it turn pale or blush for you. An enterprise to improve the style

49:10.580 --> 49:17.980
of cottage architecture. When you have got my ornaments ready, I will wear them.

49:19.920 --> 49:25.720
Before winter I built a chimney, and shingled the sides of my house, which were already

49:25.720 --> 49:32.660
impervious to rain, with imperfect and sappy shingles made of the first slice of the log

49:32.660 --> 49:40.360
whose edges I was obliged to straighten with a plane. I have, thus, a tight shingled and

49:40.360 --> 49:45.880
plastered house, ten feet wide by fifteen long, and eight feet posts, with a garret

49:45.880 --> 49:55.700
and a closet, a large window on each side, two trap-doors, one door at the end, and a

49:55.700 --> 50:02.280
compact cost of my house, paying the usual price for such materials as I used, but not

50:02.280 --> 50:08.000
counting the work, all of which was done by myself, was as follows, and I give the details

50:08.000 --> 50:13.600
because very few are able to tell exactly what their houses cost, and fewer still if

50:13.600 --> 50:21.380
any the separate cost of the various materials which compose them. Boards. Eight dollars,

50:21.380 --> 50:32.600
three cents plus. Mostly shanty boards. Refuse shingles for roof sides. Four dollars. Laths.

50:33.060 --> 50:40.200
A dollar twenty-five. Two second-hand windows with glass. Two dollars, forty-three cents.

50:42.020 --> 50:51.360
One thousand old brick. Four dollars. Two casks of lime. Two dollars, forty cents. Two

50:51.610 --> 51:02.840
that was high. Hair. Thirty-one cents. More than I needed. Mantle-tree iron. Fifteen cents.

51:03.880 --> 51:13.500
Nails. Three dollars, ninety cents. Hinges and screws. Fourteen cents. Latch. Ten cents.

51:14.420 --> 51:23.060
Chalk. One cent. Transportation. One dollar, forty cents. I carried a good part on my back.

51:23.820 --> 51:32.620
In all, twenty-eight dollars and twelve cents plus. These are all the materials, excepting

51:32.620 --> 51:39.220
the timber, stones, and sand which I claimed by squatters right. I have also a small woodshed

51:39.220 --> 51:45.100
adjoining, made chiefly of the stuff which was left after building the house. I intend

51:45.100 --> 51:50.040
to build me a house which will surpass any on the main street in Concord in grandeur

51:50.040 --> 51:57.000
and luxury, as soon as it pleases me as much and will cost me no more than my present one.

51:58.040 --> 52:03.980
I thus found that the student who wishes for a shelter can obtain one for a lifetime at

52:03.980 --> 52:11.380
an expense not greater than the rent which he now pays annually. If I seem to boast more

52:11.380 --> 52:19.760
than is becoming, my excuse is that I brag for humanity rather than for myself, and my

52:19.760 --> 52:27.020
shortcomings and inconsistencies do not affect the truth of my statement. Notwithstanding

52:27.020 --> 52:33.320
much cant and hypocrisy, chaff which I find it difficult to separate from my wheat, but

52:33.320 --> 52:40.560
for which I am as sorry as any man, I will breathe freely and stretch myself in this

52:40.560 --> 52:49.960
respect. It is such a relief to both the moral and physical system, and I am resolved that

52:49.960 --> 52:58.040
I will not, through humility, become the devil's attorney. I will endeavor to speak a good

52:58.040 --> 53:05.140
word for the truth. At Cambridge College the mere rent of a student's room, which is only

53:05.140 --> 53:12.840
a little larger than my own, is thirty dollars each year. Though the corporation had the

53:12.840 --> 53:18.980
advantage of building thirty-two side by side and under one roof, and the occupant suffers

53:18.980 --> 53:26.120
the inconvenience of many and noisy neighbors, and perhaps a residence in the fourth story,

53:26.820 --> 53:35.900
I cannot but think that if we had more true wisdom in these respects, not only less education

53:35.900 --> 53:42.740
would be needed, because for sooth more would already have been acquired, but the pecuniary

53:42.740 --> 53:49.220
expense of getting an education would in a great measure vanish. Those conveniences which

53:49.220 --> 53:56.100
the student requires at Cambridge or elsewhere cost him, or somebody else, ten times as great

53:56.120 --> 54:04.000
a sacrifice of life as they would with proper management on both sides. Those things for

54:04.000 --> 54:11.820
which the most money is demanded are never the things which the student most wants. Tuition,

54:11.860 --> 54:18.880
for instance, is an important item in the term bill, while for the far more valuable

54:18.880 --> 54:25.160
education which he gets by associating with the most cultivated of his contemporaries,

54:26.120 --> 54:33.900
no charge is made. The mode of founding a college is, commonly, to get up a subscription

54:33.900 --> 54:40.300
of dollars and cents, and then, following blindly the principles of a division of labor

54:40.300 --> 54:46.880
to its extreme, a principle which should never be followed but with circumspection, to call

54:46.880 --> 54:54.480
in a contractor who makes this a subject of speculation, and he employs Irishmen, or other

54:54.480 --> 55:01.740
cooperatives, actually, to lay the foundations, while the students that are to be are said

55:01.740 --> 55:07.960
to be fitting themselves for it, and for these oversights successive generations have to

55:07.960 --> 55:15.320
pay. I think that it would be better than this for the students, or those who desire

55:15.320 --> 55:23.440
to be benefited by it, even to lay the foundation themselves. The student who secures his coveted

55:23.440 --> 55:30.460
leisure and retirement by systematically shirking any labor necessary to man obtains

55:30.460 --> 55:38.220
but an ennoble and unprofitable leisure, defrauding himself of the experience which alone can

55:38.220 --> 55:45.680
make leisure fruitful. But, says one, you do not mean that the students should go to

55:45.680 --> 55:53.420
work with their hands instead of their heads? I do not mean that exactly, but I mean something

55:53.420 --> 56:04.140
which he might think a good deal like that. I mean that they should not play life or study

56:04.140 --> 56:12.480
it merely, while the community supports them at this expensive game, but earnestly live

56:12.480 --> 56:23.400
it from beginning to end. How could youths better learn to live than by at once trying

56:23.400 --> 56:32.120
the experiment of living? Methinks this would exercise their minds as much as mathematics?

56:33.800 --> 56:41.060
If I wished a boy to know something about the arts and sciences, for instance, I would

56:41.060 --> 56:46.060
not pursue the common course which is merely to send him into the neighborhood of some

56:46.060 --> 56:52.940
professor, where anything is professed and practiced but the art of life, to survey the

56:52.940 --> 57:01.500
world through a telescope or a microscope, and never with his natural eye, to study chemistry

57:01.980 --> 57:12.480
and not learn how his bread is made, or mechanics, and not learn how it is earned, to discover

57:12.480 --> 57:22.920
new satellites to Neptune, and not detect the motes in his eyes, or to what is known

57:22.940 --> 57:30.640
as Vagabond, he is a satellite himself, or to be devoured by the monsters that swarm

57:30.640 --> 57:37.040
all around him, while contemplating the monsters in a drop of vinegar.

57:38.820 --> 57:47.320
Which would have advanced the most at the end of a month? The boy who had made his own

57:47.320 --> 57:53.760
jack-knife from the ore which he had dug and smelted, reading as much as would be necessary

57:53.760 --> 58:00.980
for this, or the boy who had attended the lectures on metallurgy at the Institute in

58:00.980 --> 58:08.460
the meanwhile and had received a Rogers pen-knife from his father, which would be most likely

58:08.460 --> 58:15.840
to cut his fingers. To my astonishment I was informed on leaving

58:15.840 --> 58:24.520
college that I had studied navigation. Why, if I had taken one turn down the harbor I

58:24.520 --> 58:30.780
should have known more about it. Even the poor student studies and is taught only political

58:30.780 --> 58:37.860
economy, while that economy of living, which is synonymous with philosophy, is not even

58:37.860 --> 58:45.820
sincerely professed in our colleges. The consequence is that while he is reading Adam Smith, recalling

58:45.840 --> 58:50.960
Cardo and say, He runs his father in debt irretrievably.

